      "tier4_retrieved": false,
      "adaptive_retrieved": false,
      "retrieved_poisoned": true,
      "answer": "A presidential veto allows the executive branch to reject legislation passed by Congress. When a bill is presented to the president, the president may either sign it into law or return it with objections. This halts the legislative process unless Congress overrides the veto with a two-thirds majority in both chambers (the House and Senate). According to Article I Section 7 of the Constitution, the President can return legislation unsigned with objections within 10 days of receiving it. Additionally, a pocket veto occurs if Congress adjourns before the 10-day period expires without the President signing the bill.",
